author: The Star Online
title: Final voyage of a legend | The Star
text:
THE ocean liner that once carried presidents, celebrities and hopeful immigrants across the Atlantic is making its final journey ‚Äì not to a grand restoration, but to the bottom of the sea.
The SS United States, which set records and captured imaginations in the mid-20th century, departed Philadelphia last month after decades of rusting in place. It is now bound for the Florida Panhandle, where it will become the world‚Äôs largest artificial reef.
The 302m-long ship, known as the Big U, first heads to Mobile, Alabama, where hazardous materials, including remaining fuel, will be removed before it is sunk safely.
Since it can no longer move under its own power, a fleet of tugboats pulled it down the Delaware River before a single tug continued the slow tow southward into open waters.
A ship of superlatives
Built in the early 1950s, the SS United States remains the largest passenger ship ever constructed in America, over 30m longer than the Titanic.
Designed by naval architect William Francis Gibbs, it served as a luxury liner in peacetime but could be swiftly converted to transport 14,000 troops if needed.
The ship made history on its maiden voyage, setting a transatlantic speed record by reaching Europe in just over three days at an average of more than 65kph.
Over the years, it made 800 Atlantic crossings, hosting the famous and the ordinary alike.
However, as air travel became dominant, the ship was withdrawn from service in 1969.
A bittersweet farewell
On Feb 19, tugboats guided the ship under the Walt Whitman Bridge, where traffic was briefly halted as its towering funnels cleared the roadway by less than 3m.
Spectators gathered to watch history move once more.
Garfield Harper Jr, a New Jersey resident, had been there when the ship arrived in Philadelphia in 1996. Seeing it depart again stirred memories.
‚ÄúMy life is just about gone ‚Äì I‚Äôm in my 70s,‚Äù he reflected. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs kind of sad, but I just wanted to see it leave.‚Äù
Five days earlier, a small crowd had watched as the ship was carefully moved from its longtime berth to another pier in South Philadelphia.
The peeling black hull loomed over the industrial waterfront as tugboats nudged it across the slip ‚Äì a short but symbolic step in its final voyage.
For some, the departure was deeply personal.
Spectators watching the ‚ÄòSS United States‚Äô depart Philadelphia under tow on its final voyage, near Gloucester City, New Jersey. ‚Äî Rachel Wisniewski/The New York Times
Stephen Kosciesza, 70, from Maryland, recalled how his parents immigrated aboard the SS United States in 1954.
His father, a stateless Polish refugee, was seasick for much of the journey.
‚ÄúThe famous family story is that all the way over, he was saying, ‚ÄòCommodore, stop the ship! I‚Äôm getting out,‚Äô‚Äù Kosciesza chuckled.
The end of an era
Many had long hoped to see the ship preserved as a museum or attraction.
Devin Harrison, a maritime enthusiast from Pennsylvania, lamented its fate. ‚ÄúI think it should be a national treasure,‚Äù he said.
The SS United States Conservancy, which purchased the ship in 2011, had fought for years to secure a future for it.
However, after a federal court ordered its eviction from the Philadelphia pier last summer, the group raced to find a new home.
Efforts to secure a berth at major ports across the United States all failed due to the ship‚Äôs immense size.
As Susan Gibbs, head of the conservancy and granddaughter of the ship‚Äôs designer, put it, ‚ÄúShe‚Äôs just so darn big.‚Äù
In the end, the best available option was to transform the ship into an artificial reef.
Once sunk in about 55m of water off the Gulf Coast, its highest points will still sit 18m below the surface.
Plans are also in place for a land-based museum in Florida, which will incorporate preserved elements of the vessel, including at least one of its funnels.
Alex Fogg, a marine resources expert involved in the project, said the reef would provide a thriving habitat for fish, crabs and other sea life. He believes it will also become a major destination for divers worldwide.
A magnificent journey
For many admirers of the SS United States, its final resting place is a painful but dignified compromise.
Linda Silva, 80, sailed aboard the ship as a young woman on a life-changing voyage to Paris.
‚ÄúNo one in my family had ever done anything like that,‚Äù she recalled.
While saddened by its fate, she accepts the inevitability.
‚ÄúIt‚Äôs not that life is a decline,‚Äù she mused.
‚ÄúSometimes your usefulness kind of terminates abruptly, as hers did. But it doesn‚Äôt overshadow the magnificent journey you took to get there.‚Äù ‚Äî ¬©2025 The New York Times Company

title: Does It Snow in New Mexico? Snowiest Places and Averages
text: New Mexico is a beautiful state. Its landscapes will leave you breathless everywhere you look. It just makes sense why the state is called The Land of Enchantment . The indigenous culture and history, the colorful gemstones, the cactus-filled deserts, the deep caverns, the stunning snowy mountains in winter ‚Äî everything about New Mexico is enchanting. But does it snow in New Mexico? Yes, it does snow in New Mexico. Usually, the snowy season starts in November and ends in March. The northern and central parts of the state get the most amounts of snowfall, but anywhere in the state where the elevation is higher will get snow. The snowiest place in New Mexico is Red River. Let‚Äôs take a look at where most of the snow in New Mexico takes place, the average amounts, temperatures, and more. Believe it or not, the place in New Mexico that got snow at the earliest time was in Estancia on September 24, 1913. ¬©Roschetzky Photography/Shutterstock.com The average amount of snow that New Mexico gets depends on the region you are in. For example, the northern, mountainous regions of New Mexico will get snow often. In the south, like the desert areas and the plains of the state, you can expect to get about 3 inches per year. In the mountainous areas of New Mexico, you can expect to see somewhere between 100 to 300 inches of snow every year. The table shows the average amount of snow for Red River, NM, during the colder months between November and March. As you can see, February, on average, gets the most snow per year. During winter, New Mexico isn‚Äôt too cold, but it isn‚Äôt warm either. Winters can get to around 40 degrees Fahrenheit. But in the northern and central parts of the state, the temperatures can go way down and some parts can even experience freezing temperatures. The months of December, January, and February are usually the coldest of the year ‚Äî with an average of 18 degrees to 43 degrees. When it comes to records, the city of Gavilan recorded -50 degrees on February 1, 1951. The snowiest place in New Mexico is Red River, which is located in Northern New Mexico. ¬©Roschetzky Photography/Shutterstock.com Usually, the snowiest places in New Mexico are located in the northern part of the state, as well as the central part of the state. The snowiest place in New Mexico is Red River , located above Taos, NM. It snows an average of 62 days every year with over 40 inches of snow. Other snowy places in the state include Santa Fe , which snows about 22 inches every year, and Taos, and the areas surrounding the city. The biggest snowstorm in New Mexico‚Äôs history was recorded in Socorro County with a whopping 41 inches. ¬©Jeff Kingma/iStock via Getty Images Like all Southwestern states, New Mexico is a very biodiverse state . There are deserts, mountains, and everything that you can imagine in this land of enchantment. You can also find a variety of animals that can be unique to New Mexico. The animals that you can spot in the state include Bighorn sheep, cougars, deer, and ibexes. If you look up, you may be able to see Eurasian collared doves and other birds. New Mexico‚Äôs winter animals include many species of geese, more than you would ever imagine like Arctic snow geese and even sandhill cranes. And there you have it, it does snow in New Mexico. The snow that occurs in New Mexico is usually centralized in the northern part of the state. However even though it is unlikely, there has been snow reported in other parts of New Mexico. Usually where the elevation is higher and the temperatures are lower is where you will find the most snow. As you drive down the highway to go to the snowiest place in New Mexico, look around you and see the beauty of the state. The post Does It Snow in New Mexico? Snowiest Places and Averages appeared first on A-Z Animals .
